<paragraph blockId="12.[264,1323,1481,1867]" lastBlockId="13.[264,1323,284,430]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName box="[398,540,1481,1506]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Acmanthina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[398,540,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Acmanthina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes two species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Meyrick" authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1824" box="[812,1101,1481,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Peronea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acmanthes">
<emphasis box="[812,972,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. acmanthes</emphasis>
(Meyrick)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown" authorityName="Brown" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Acmanthina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipuncta">
<emphasis box="[1162,1322,1481,1506]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. albipuncta</emphasis>
Brown
</taxonomicName>
, both of which are recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[783,847,1521,1547]" name="Chile" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Chile</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[915,1036,1521,1547]" name="Argentina" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Argentina</collectingCountry>
. Adults are moderately small, with a dark forewing bearing variable white patch(es) and/or band(s), superficially most similar to some species of 
<taxonomicName box="[655,786,1601,1626]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Apotomops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[655,786,1601,1626]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Apotomops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[849,963,1601,1626]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Bonagota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[849,963,1601,1626]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Bonagota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Brown" box="[1029,1192,1601,1627]" pageId="12" pageNumber="21" refString="Brown, J. W. (2000 b) Acmanthina: a new genus of tortricid moths (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae) from Chile and Argentina. Journal of the New York Entomological Society, 108, 106 - 113." type="journal article" year="2000" yearSuffix="b">
Brown 
<number box="[1119,1178,1601,1627]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2000.0">2000</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
for photographs of adults). Males can be distinguished from those of related genera by the absence of the fine, elongate scales along the basal portions of hindwing veins CuP and 
<number box="[1226,1236,1681,1707]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="1.0">1</number>
A+ 
<number box="[1278,1293,1681,1707]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="2.0">2</number>
A, the possession of a long, slender hairpencil of setiform scales concealed in a deep fold of hindwing vein CuP, and the deeply excavated mesal portion of the juxta, all of which are interpreted as synapomorphies for the two included species (
<taxonomicName authority="Curtis, 1824" authorityName="Curtis" authorityYear="1824" box="[1005,1167,1801,1826]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Peronea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acmanthes">
<emphasis box="[1005,1167,1801,1826]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. acmanthes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Brown" authorityName="Brown" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Acmanthina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipuncta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. albipuncta</emphasis>
Brown
</taxonomicName>
). Male genitalia are illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[840,935,1841,1867]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="25.[264,382,1694,1718]" captionTargetBox="[313,1273,333,1667]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[313,1273,326,1670]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Male genitalia of Haemateulia and Acmanthina; valvae spread, aedeagus removed (to left of capsule). 10, H. haematitis; 11, H. barrigana 12, A. albipuncta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156578/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Figs. 
<number box="[906,935,1841,1867]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[996,1028,1841,1867]" captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 15" captionStartId="26.[264,382,1694,1718]" captionTargetBox="[313,1269,330,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@26.[313,1273,326,1670]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 15. Male genitalia of Acmanthina and Apotomops; valvae spread, aedeagus removed (to left of capsule). 13, Acmanthina acmanthes; 14, Apotomops boliviana 15, Apotomops spomotopa." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156579/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<number box="[996,1028,1841,1867]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1181,1323,1841,1866]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Acmanthina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1181,1323,1841,1866]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Acmanthina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack the accessory pouch from the ductus bursae that is present in 
<taxonomicName box="[1067,1181,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Bonagota" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1067,1181,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Bonagota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Apotomops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Apotomops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[342,430,324,350]" captionStart="FIGURES 22 – 27" captionStartId="28.[264,382,1694,1718]" captionTargetBox="[335,1269,326,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[313,1273,326,1670]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 22 – 27. Female genitalia of Haemateulia, Acmanthina, Apotomops, and Bonagota. 22, H. haematitis. 23, H. barrigana; 24, Acmanthina acmanthes; 25, Apotomps boliviana; 26, Apotomops spomotopa; 27, Bonagota arizonae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156581/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Fig. 
<number box="[397,430,324,350]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="24.0">24</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[264,1323,284,430]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
The hindwing hairpencil consists of a fascicle of 
<number box="[910,981,364,390]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="22.0" valueMax="24.0" valueMin="20.0">20–24</number>
long, fine, slender, setiform scales, unlike the distally spatulate scales of the hairpencil of male 
<taxonomicName box="[1050,1197,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Ptychocroca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1050,1197,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ptychocroca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
